BUGHTLIN: A recent development in the East Craigs area names streets after the Bughtlin Burn which flows nearby. The word has a Gaelic derivation: { {'bught'}means a sheep or cattle fold and {'linne'}means a burn.
DRUMBRAE: The old name was Drum Road. The word {'drum'}means hill and so does {'brae'}- so the new name means {'Hill hill'.}
CLERMISTON: All the streets with this name take the name from the original narrow road over Corstorphine Hill. The area was {CLERBANDISTUN } originally; a medieval owner was called{Clerebald.
LADYWELL: In 1745 a spring was found at the west end of Corstorphine High Street - called{"WELL OF OUR LADY".}
